        The documentation for the SetÂ­Parent function says 
When you change the parent of a window, you should synchronize the UISTATE of both windows. For more information, see WM_CHANGEÂ­UIÂ­STATE and WM_UPDATEÂ­UIÂ­STATE. 
What does that mean? 
Recall how the WM_UPDATEÂ­UIÂ­STATE and WM_CHANGEÂ­UIÂ­STATE messages work. When keyboard indicators need to be shown or hidden, the control that initiates the change sends itself a WM_UPDATEÂ­UIÂ­STATE message. This message propages up the window tree. When it reaches the root of the tree, the message converts to a WM_CHANGEÂ­UIÂ­STATE message and propagates down the tree. 
There is an optimization here: If the desired keyboard state is already present, then message propagation stops, because thereâ€™s no point telling people to change something to what it already is. 
However, this optimization assumes that every window in the tree has the same state to begin with. 
Letâ€™s see what happens if you violate this assumption. 


