The remark in the documentation is trying to tell you that if you are moving windows between parents, and the new parent has a different UI state from its adopted child, then you have two problems: 

The UI state is inconsistent within the top-level window,     so your window looks weird.
The UI state will not be properly updated,     so your window acts weird.

Okay, so you get it. Itâ€™s important to get the two UI states in sync. But how do you do that? Weâ€™ll start looking into that next time. 
Bonus chatter: That section of the documentation was written by someone who understands the window manager so deeply that they assume everybody else understands it to the same degree, expecting that â€œsynchronize the UI stateâ€ is something the reader would comprehend immediately. (And as weâ€™ll see next time, somebody who has never actually tried to synchronize the UI states of two windows, because if they had tried, they would have realized that accomplishing the task is harder than an offhand remark would suggest.) 

        
                

        
		
                

            
            
                
